On November 2, 2017, the President signed several laws. These include the "Veterans' Compensation Cost-of-Living Adjustment Act of 2017," which provides a cost-of-living adjustment for veterans' disability compensation and dependency and indemnity compensation. Another law signed was the "Strengthening State and Local Cyber Crime Fighting Act of 2017," which establishes a National Computer Forensics Institute within the Department of Homeland Security's United States Secret Service. Additionally, the "Frederick Douglass Bicentennial Commission Act" was signed, which establishes a commission to honor Frederick Douglass on the bicentennial anniversary of his birth. Other laws include the "Power And Security Systems (PASS) Act," the "Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation Business Travel Cards Act of 2017," the "National Clinical Care Commission Act," and the designation of a United States Border Patrol checkpoint in Texas.